Elihu having laid down this general Doctrine, makes Application of it in the two verſes following;


      Verſ. 16.
    Even ſo would he have removed thee out of the ſtrait into a broad place.

For anſwer to this, when the text ſaith, God is great and we know him not; we may ſay, Firſt, That even heathens, the untaught, untutored, and uncatechized heathens do, or, may know

 God, that is, they may know him in ſome degree or other, they may, yea, they do know him (as the Apoſtle ſaith, Rom. 1.20.) ſo far as to leave them without excuſe; they have no plea, nor can they make any apologie for themſelves. Secondly, 'Tis certain, all believers, I mean all true believers, know God ſavingly, or ſo far as is ſufficient for their ſalvation. Every believer knows God. There is no faith in God without the knowledge of God. Thirdly, Which ſhall be the point of Obſervation from this part, as well as an anſwer to the queſtion;
None know God fully, perfectly, comprehenſively.

